### 🐛 Describe the bug

Some update between v0.11 and v0.16 made the following configuration unusable, as mixed prefill-decode performance is, who knows, about 10-100x (yes, x, not %) slower or so, spending most of (not all) the time at 0tk/s. No errors, no wrong answers, it's just terribly slow. Unfortunately, I have no idea when the issue started because v0.11 works fine and I never updated until now (as required for Qwen3.5 compatibility), and there are no Docker images older than 0.15.1 available that I could find. I'm not capable of setting up a native Linux environment, or build the older versions for source, etc., for testing at this point. A fix for v0.16 would be needed anyway for Qwen3.5 support.

Issue didn't exist in v0.11. Issue happens in both the oldest available (v0.15.1) and 0.16.1rc1.dev92+gf5d1281c9 Docker Hub versions. Running on WSL2. 2x RTX 3090. Can't be a hardware/OS limitation since v0.11 still works correctly.

Tests below were all with Qwen3 (to minimize changed variables), but issue is identical with Qwen3.5 in v0.16 (3.5 is even slower, in fact, but I suppose it's expected with the newer architecture).

GPU is clearly underutilized, throughput and power usage are both noticeably lower during mixed prefill/decode (~180W per GPU instead of being pegged to 280W set power limit otherwise).

I didn't find any already filed bug that's nearly as extreme. #34681 and #35048 are probably the closest, but I'm not sure they're actually related to this at all.  The https://docs.vllm.ai/ chatbot suggested some issues that are clearly unrelated (engine not starting at all, reduced context sizes, etc.), not "pure" performance regressions that silently seem work normally despite stalling to almost zero speed.

All I'm looking for is to have high ingestion speed and high throughput while still having acceptable low-load/single-request performance. Which should be possible, since v0.11 delivers it, but I can't find any user-configurable flag that restores that performance in v0.16, hence this bug report.

What I tried:

```plaintext
--no-async-scheduling  	 		# no change, still broken for mixed prefill/decode, ingestion unusably slow;
-e VLLM_USE_AOT_COMPILE=0 	 	# no change, still broken for mixed prefill/decode, ingestion unusably slow;
--optimization-level 1 	 		# no change, still broken for mixed prefill/decode, ingestion unusably slow;
--optimization-level 2 	 		# default, still broken for mixed prefill/decode, ingestion unusably slow;
--optimization-level 3 	 		# no change, still broken for mixed prefill/decode, ingestion unusably slow;
--compilation-config "{\"cudagraph_mode\":\"PIECEWISE\"}"					# no change, fast for 1 request, still broken for mixed prefill/decode, ingestion unusably slow;
--compilation-config "{\"cudagraph_mode\":\"FULL_DECODE_ONLY\"}" 	 		# no change, fastest for 1 request, still broken for mixed prefill/decode, ingestion unusably slow;
--compilation-config "{\"cudagraph_capture_sizes\":[512,504,496,488,480,472,464,456,448,440,432,424,416,408,400,392,384,376,368,360,352,344,336,328,320,312,304,296,288,280,272,264,256,248,240,232,224,216,208,200,192,184,176,168,160,152,144,136,128,120,112,104,96,88,80,72,64,56,48,40,32,24,16,8,4,2,1]}" 	 		# to set it to same sizes as 0.11, just in case, no change;

--enable-prefix-caching  	 	# required for workload, no change anyway;
--kv_cache_dtype fp8_e4m3		# required for workload, untested at FP16 as it wouldn't have enough context size anyway;
--disable-custom-all-reduce		# always disabled for WSL

Changing attention backend from Flashinfer to Triton makes it not even start;

--enforce-eager 			# "fixes" it but makes performance with single request is unusable (~27tk/s instead of >80 in Qwen3, even worse 15tk/s vs 67tk/s in Qwen3.5), still slower at mixed prefill/decode load than 0.11.
--optimization-level 0 		# "fixes" it with the same caveats as above.
--compilation-config "{\"cudagraph_mode\":\"NONE\"}"					# "fixes" it with the same caveats as above.

```

